    # Convert the input1 string to a list of integers
    numbers = list(map(int, input1.strip('[]').split()))
    target = input2
    
    # Variables to track the best pair and smallest difference
    best_pair = (None, None)
    smallest_difference = float('inf')
    
    # Iterate over all pairs of numbers
    for i in range(len(numbers)):
        for j in range(i + 1, len(numbers)):
            num1 = numbers[i]
            num2 = numbers[j]
            current_sum = num1 + num2
            current_difference = abs(target - current_sum)
            
            # Check if this pair is closer to the target
            if current_difference < smallest_difference:
                best_pair = (num1, num2)

    return best_pair

def my_func(input1, input2):
    """
    This function accepts a list of integers (input1) and an integer (input2),
    and returns two integers from input1 whose sum is closest to input2.
    """
    # Convert input1 string to a list of integers
    input1 = list(map(int, input1.strip('[]').split()))
    
    # Initialize variables to store the best pair and the smallest difference
    best_pair = (None, None)
    smallest_diff = float('inf')
    
    # Iterate over all possible pairs in input1
    for i in range(len(input1)):
        for j in range(i + 1, len(input1)):
            # Calculate the sum of the current pair
            current_sum = input1[i] + input1[j]
            # Calculate the difference from input2
            current_diff = abs(current_sum - input2)
            
            # Update the best pair if the current pair is better
            if (current_diff < smallest_diff or
                (current_diff == smallest_diff and input1[i] < best_pair[0]) or
                (current_diff == smallest_diff and input1[i] == best_pair[0] and input1[j] < best_pair[1])):
                best_pair = (input1[i], input1[j])
                smallest_diff = current_diff
    
    return best_pair
